        "text": "A haunting soundtrack in this immersive film about intersecting destinies and the existential condition of the human soul on this Earth, tackling a range of subjects deeply relevant to today's world, such as colonisation and rebellion in this climate of war and destructive imperialism, while tackling the conflicts with depth and humanity\n\nEcology, with the devastation of the Niger Delta, crudely represented and always a good reason to say fuck capitalism and the oil companies.\n\nIt's also the story of a disillusionment, of a broken dream, a cinematic gem both political and artistic, with very few dialogues, everything in the glances, the guilt taking over, plunging us into a state of discomfort, a kind of waking nightmare, with its heavy…\n\nA dance of the dead. Disco Boy is a film of lives far apart, drawn together through circumstance and death. On the one hand it is the story of a soldier, an immigrant joining the French Foreign Legion to sell his soul for a passport. Yet simultaneously it is the story of African lands exploited and those fighting to free them. There are so many shots of the Niger Delta with industry and pollution lingering in the background. The oppression comes not just from political rule but also economic conquest. Disco Boy is about two men forced to take up arms, one through obligation to his people and another just hired to do France's dirty work.\n\nDisco Boy takes some…"
